To terminate a C program, you can use the exit() function. The exit() function takes an integer as an argument, which is the status code returned to the operating system. The default status code is 0, which means the program terminated normally. If you want to terminate the program with an error, you can pass a non-zero value as the argument. For example, if you want to terminate the program with an error, you can use the following code:
```
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // code
    exit(1);
    return 0;
}
```
Alternatively, you can use the return statement to terminate the program. The return statement returns the control to the calling function, and the program terminates. For example:
```
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // code
    return 1;
}
```
You can also use the abort() function to terminate the program. The abort() function terminates the program immediately, without executing any further code. For example:
```
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    // code
    abort();
    return 0;
}
```
Note that the abort() function is not portable across all platforms, so it is generally recommended to use the exit() function instead.
